1. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper deals with the partial sums problem and presents two succinct versions of the Fenwick Tree. This is a classic data structure problem and falls under the purview of cs.DS. 
2. cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) - The paper mentions that the results allow for simple optimal parallelization. This indicates that the paper may be relevant to the field of distributed and parallel computing. 
3. cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) - The paper uses bit-packing and sampling techniques, which are commonly used in discrete mathematics. 
4. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) - The paper discusses the time complexity of the sum/update operations and presents results that achieve optimal time complexity. This may be of interest to researchers in the field of computational complexity. 
5. cs.DL (Digital Libraries) - This is a less likely category, but the paper does mention the encoding model where one is allowed to reuse the space from the input data. This may be relevant to researchers working on digital libraries and information retrieval.
